# UI Design Consistency

When building any new page, section, or component, follow these rules:

- Prefer existing components from `@ui` before creating custom UI.
- Reuse `@ui` primitives for buttons, inputs, selects, modals, tooltips, badges, toggles, checkboxes, and similar controls.
- Keep spacing, typography, radius, colors, and interaction behavior aligned with the current system design.
- If a required variant is missing, extend the closest existing `@ui` component instead of introducing a separate design pattern.

## Examples

```vue
<!-- ❌ BAD: custom button style that bypasses design system -->
<button class="px-3 py-2 rounded bg-blue-600 text-white">Save</button>
```

```vue
<!-- ✅ GOOD: reuse shared UI component -->
<UiButton color="primary">Save</UiButton>
```

```vue
<!-- ✅ GOOD: compose UI from system components -->
<UiModal>
  <template #header>Confirm Action</template>
  <UiCheckbox v-model="confirmed">I understand</UiCheckbox>
  <UiButton color="danger">Delete</UiButton>
</UiModal>
```
